WEBVTT

00:08.980 --> 00:12.920
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.540 --> 00:33.860
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.860 --> 00:38.160
And here are your hosts.

00:42.340 --> 00:44.360
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane.

00:44.640 --> 00:47.980
Howard Waldrop is a science fiction writer whose stories began appearing in the early

00:47.980 --> 00:51.000
1970s and he's written some remarkably good ones.

00:51.440 --> 00:54.780
His reputation as one of science fiction's finest short story writers is growing.

00:55.480 --> 01:00.620
Waldrop's The Ugly Chickens won a nebula award in 1981 and God's Hooks was a 1983 nebula

01:00.620 --> 01:01.340
finalist.

01:01.680 --> 01:04.140
I Cut the Mic is a 1983 Hugo finalist.

01:04.600 --> 01:08.580
Waldrop wrote for fanzines as a teenager but finally he was inspired to write science

01:08.580 --> 01:08.960
fiction.

01:09.460 --> 01:10.940
Here he tells us what inspired him.

01:11.640 --> 01:17.460
Well, actually, if you want to know, everybody has a story like this but I read Lynn Carter's

01:18.180 --> 01:23.860
Wizards of Lemuria and I said if he can get that published, I can write, I can get that,

01:24.040 --> 01:25.360
you know, I can get my stuff published.

01:26.000 --> 01:27.020
It's real obvious.

01:27.560 --> 01:29.540
I mean, everybody, I think, has a story about that.

01:29.620 --> 01:32.060
They read something after they've been reading this for 20 years.

01:32.540 --> 01:38.180
They finally read something that just pushes their buttons and says, that's garbage, you

01:38.180 --> 01:41.300
know, I can write better than that even when you're 18 years old.

01:41.440 --> 01:42.640
He said, I can write better than that.

01:42.840 --> 01:43.980
And you set out to prove it.

01:44.100 --> 01:48.520
And a lot of people set out to prove it, write a story and like submit it or don't submit

01:48.520 --> 01:50.000
it, just write the story to prove it.

01:50.100 --> 01:52.220
They can write a story, you know, not even writing a story.

01:52.460 --> 01:54.780
So essentially is I got serious.

02:03.080 --> 02:06.260
Walter was first professional sale was a story called Lunchbox.

02:06.760 --> 02:08.360
We asked him how he initially got published.

02:09.500 --> 02:14.180
Essentially, I had been trying to get published since 1966.

02:14.540 --> 02:16.680
Been serious about it, 65 and 66.

02:17.540 --> 02:20.980
And I'd been publishing in fanzines all along, stories in fanzines.

02:21.420 --> 02:25.580
And I just kept sending the stories out until finally one of them sold.

02:26.280 --> 02:29.800
I mean, there was no problem breaking in as such.

02:29.800 --> 02:32.860
I mean, it wasn't like a conscious thing saying, this is the one I'm going to break

02:32.860 --> 02:35.100
in with or I'm going to write a story to break in.

02:35.140 --> 02:38.700
It was just I'd been sending them out and getting them back until one day I sent one

02:38.700 --> 02:39.960
out and it didn't come back.

02:40.400 --> 02:41.700
You know, check came back.

02:43.400 --> 02:47.300
And that's, you know, it was like I'd been, I'd been writing for fanzines all along in

02:47.300 --> 02:48.660
comic scripts and things like that.

02:49.380 --> 02:53.620
And the story just came, I mean, when it was time for it to sell, it's old.

02:54.540 --> 02:58.800
Lunchbox details the fate of the first Viking lander shortly after it touches down on Mars

02:58.800 --> 03:03.740
since the story was written prior to the actual Viking landing, but was published after the

03:03.740 --> 03:04.580
landing took place.

03:04.980 --> 03:07.660
We ask Waldrop if any changes had to be made in the interim.

03:08.060 --> 03:13.500
I sold that story in 1969 or not in 69 and 70.

03:13.680 --> 03:18.040
And I sold it four days or I got the letter four days after I was drafted in the army.

03:18.660 --> 03:23.600
And but because John Kimmel, it was so analog because John Kimmel died in the meantime and

03:23.600 --> 03:29.800
everything was in and uproar at Street and Smith for about, or Condon asked for six months

03:29.800 --> 03:30.180
or so.

03:31.000 --> 03:35.660
Ben Bova wrote me a letter in 1972 and said, I'm changing all.

03:35.780 --> 03:37.400
The original it was called Voyager.

03:37.720 --> 03:41.160
If you remember the Viking, the Viking stuff was all called Voyager.

03:41.280 --> 03:44.540
And the whole story was talking about the Voyager lander and all this kind of stuff.

03:45.020 --> 03:49.620
And Ben Bova wrote and says, is it okay if I change, change Voyager to Viking so you

03:49.620 --> 03:50.380
won't look like a jerk?

03:50.600 --> 03:51.800
And I said, why sure, Ben?

03:51.800 --> 03:53.200
Yeah, you know, anything you want.

03:53.860 --> 03:58.440
And you know, because the technology changed the, the changed the term, you know, the terminology

03:58.440 --> 03:59.020
in the meantime.

03:59.280 --> 04:01.760
And, you know, I'd been in the army and what was that?

04:01.940 --> 04:06.820
You know, I was guarding PX's and stuff, you know, and you know, I hadn't been kept up

04:06.820 --> 04:10.280
on the change in terminology in the meantime, you know.

04:10.600 --> 04:16.280
But yes, it was, it preceded, there were, there were several prototype models of the,

04:16.360 --> 04:20.940
essentially what became the Viking lander all competing for, for the contract in the

04:20.940 --> 04:21.820
late 60s.

04:22.860 --> 04:25.240
And the Voyager thing was one of them.

04:25.460 --> 04:30.420
And I've got a, I've got a picture I visited Langley for one of the mock-ups of the, of

04:30.420 --> 04:36.640
the original Voyager thing, which was slightly, it looked much the same as the Viking eventually

04:36.640 --> 04:40.140
was, but had, you know, longer arm and all this kind of stuff, you know.

04:42.020 --> 04:44.980
But anyway, yeah, it, it preceded the program.

04:44.980 --> 04:50.620
So that's why, you know, the change to Viking was, you know, like, fitted into the story.

