06:29.100 --> 06:32.760
Science fiction writer Howard Walder collaborated with several writers on short stories in the

06:32.760 --> 06:36.960
1970s, including Stephen Utley, Buddy Saunders, George Proctor, and George Martin.

06:37.420 --> 06:40.060
We asked Walder why these collaborations took place.

06:40.900 --> 06:45.600
There was a group of us, and we all, it's, it's, it's amazing that it happened.

06:46.320 --> 06:51.200
We're all from, we're all from Texas, living in Texas, and we all published our first story

06:51.200 --> 06:53.260
within like six or eight months of each other.

06:53.360 --> 06:53.900
It was amazing.

06:54.080 --> 06:54.940
It just happened that way.

06:55.380 --> 06:59.480
And we all got, got, got to meet each other at conventions within like six months of our

06:59.480 --> 07:00.560
first story is being published.

07:02.900 --> 07:05.000
And we were all writing at the same time.

07:05.080 --> 07:07.400
We were all serious about this stuff we were going to take over.

07:08.520 --> 07:12.160
And one of the ways we did it was we started collaborating with each other.

07:12.640 --> 07:16.360
And we'd do stories on our own, but then we'd also do stories that we couldn't do on our

07:16.360 --> 07:17.220
own with the other people.

07:18.440 --> 07:21.160
And it wasn't a conscious effort on anybody's part.

07:21.340 --> 07:24.040
I think it just, one of those things that just happened, you know, we were just all

07:24.040 --> 07:24.940
writing at the same time.

07:25.020 --> 07:26.100
We were all right there.

07:26.280 --> 07:29.020
Like Buddy was my landlord, you know, he owned one half a duplex.

07:29.020 --> 07:29.860
And I was any other.

07:30.460 --> 07:33.920
And he, of course, he got me into comics fandom 10 years before that anyway.

07:35.040 --> 07:36.580
And some of us were friends.

07:36.720 --> 07:39.480
Some of us met each other and became friends and things like that.

07:39.940 --> 07:46.040
And it's just that we just, we just sparked each other, you know, if you, if you had something

07:46.040 --> 07:49.360
you were doing and you got through with it and you weren't quite ready to do something

07:49.360 --> 07:54.760
else, you could always, you know, do a collaboration with Buddy or with, or with Proctor or with,

07:54.820 --> 07:57.040
you know, you know, anything like that.

07:57.040 --> 08:02.560
And like we just, there must have been in space of about two years, there must have

08:02.560 --> 08:08.820
been 35 or 40 stories come out of the various collaborations, you know, two and sometimes

08:08.820 --> 08:12.560
three way collaborations with people, you know, it was amazing.

08:12.780 --> 08:14.120
And it's amazing that it happened.

08:14.300 --> 08:17.960
And it's amazing that we got so much done on our own too, besides doing all that.

08:25.060 --> 08:29.640
One of these collaborations of voice and bitter weeping written with Buddy Saunders was expanded

08:29.640 --> 08:31.900
to a novel, the Texas-Israeli War, 1999.

08:32.660 --> 08:34.600
We asked Walter how this transformation occurred.

08:35.100 --> 08:39.900
We originally wrote that story before I sold Lunchbox even.

08:39.900 --> 08:46.720
Buddy and I did this 10,000 word novella or novel ad in alternate chapters.

08:47.520 --> 08:53.280
Like, you know, as, as in the novel, as in the first like 50 pages novel, we tried to sell

08:53.280 --> 08:56.360
that thing everywhere and it would not sell.

08:56.660 --> 09:01.500
I did, you know, it got up to the point where the battleship, the battle with the

09:01.500 --> 09:05.400
battleship or the cruiser in, in Dallas, that was where the thing ended.

09:07.120 --> 09:08.780
And it wouldn't sell anywhere.

09:08.920 --> 09:11.800
And I went in the army and Buddy quit trying to market it while I was in the army.

09:12.140 --> 09:17.060
Well, when I came out of the army and I started selling stories and all this stuff and everybody

09:17.060 --> 09:19.660
started selling stories, Buddy started writing again.

09:19.980 --> 09:24.680
He also took voice and bitter weeping, took all my parts out of it, in other words, half

09:24.680 --> 09:29.760
the story just by leaving the parts he'd written in and sold it first thing off to a galaxy.

09:31.060 --> 09:31.860
And OK.

09:32.160 --> 09:33.700
And then he sold it to Galaxy.

09:35.040 --> 09:38.640
Judy Lindell Ray was the assistant editor at Galaxy and had just been hired by

09:38.640 --> 09:40.380
Ballantyne Books as their SF editor.

09:40.800 --> 09:45.020
The last thing she saw before she left Galaxy was our story and she liked it and she wrote

09:45.020 --> 09:47.720
it and she said, I like this story a lot.

09:47.880 --> 09:51.360
Do you think you could come up with a, with an outline for a novel?

09:51.580 --> 09:53.680
And if you do, I'll offer you so much and so much.

09:53.720 --> 09:55.140
And we went, oh, wow, you know.

09:56.100 --> 10:00.380
So we said, not only do we have an outline, we sit down and like continue the outline

10:00.380 --> 10:02.420
as the book goes like in one night.

10:02.420 --> 10:06.520
So we said, not only do we have an outline, but the first 10,000 words are already written.

10:06.960 --> 10:08.460
You know, just like that.

10:08.580 --> 10:11.620
We just stuck my parts back in the alternate chapters back in.

10:11.700 --> 10:13.280
We had 10,000 words of the book already.

10:13.360 --> 10:16.300
All we had to do is write another 45,000 words, you know.

10:18.020 --> 10:21.120
And they wrote back, you know, they accepted the outline and gave us contract.

10:21.380 --> 10:22.760
And that was, you know, we wrote the book.

10:23.240 --> 10:24.620
That was, it was a stroke of luck.

10:24.760 --> 10:25.760
It was just a stroke of luck.

10:25.920 --> 10:30.000
We were, it was at the right place at the right time, you know, two, two weeks before or two

10:30.000 --> 10:31.980
weeks later, it wouldn't have, that wouldn't have happened probably.

