12:08.060 --> 12:13.100
In 1976, a collaboration between Howard Waldrup and Stephen Utley produced the nebula finalist

12:13.100 --> 12:15.040
novelette, Custer's Last Jump.

12:15.480 --> 12:19.360
Custer's Last Jump is an immensely detailed alternate world story, which begins with the

12:19.360 --> 12:20.300
American Civil War.

12:20.740 --> 12:24.880
In this alternate history, both the Union and the Confederacy have airplanes, which figure

12:24.880 --> 12:25.820
heavily in the war.

12:26.200 --> 12:31.320
During the conflict, the Ogala Sioux leader, Crazy Horse, manages to acquire and secrete

12:31.320 --> 12:32.340
a few planes himself.

12:32.880 --> 12:36.780
In 1876, these planes are used in a climactic battle against Custer.

12:37.240 --> 12:38.860
Waldrup explains how the story was written.

12:39.700 --> 12:41.640
Utley had always been a Custer freak.

12:42.400 --> 12:44.060
He knew all about all that stuff.

12:44.720 --> 12:48.020
I'd always been an airplane freak, so I knew all about the airplane stuff.

12:48.680 --> 12:52.340
And we started one night in 1972.

12:52.820 --> 12:54.280
It was like November of 1972.

12:54.980 --> 12:58.240
We started playing, can you top this on a typewriter?

12:58.560 --> 12:58.820
You know?

12:58.820 --> 13:06.040
And so Utley wrote this section about part of the second part, the Collier's article.

13:06.500 --> 13:09.320
We're about two pages that, and he read it to me over the phone.

13:09.800 --> 13:14.000
And about an hour later, I rang him back up and read the first five, you know, first

13:14.000 --> 13:20.380
three pages of the part of the Smithsonian report about Crazy Horse's airplane.

13:20.780 --> 13:22.740
And we just went crazy from there, you know?

13:23.040 --> 13:26.900
And like the story was written in like six days or something like that.

13:27.740 --> 13:31.640
I did a tremendous amount of research in the time between the time we started the

13:31.640 --> 13:33.100
story and the time we finished it, you know?

13:33.560 --> 13:35.520
One of the things was it was written in the alternate.

13:36.440 --> 13:38.000
I wrote the airplane part.

13:38.380 --> 13:39.540
Utley wrote the Collier's article.

13:41.080 --> 13:45.860
Steve wrote the twain part because he'd always been fascinated by Mark Twain.

13:46.420 --> 13:52.660
And then I wrote the Testament of Black Man's Hand, you know, that twain transcribes

13:52.660 --> 13:53.300
in the story.

13:53.900 --> 13:56.560
And then we both sat down and wrote the bibliography together.

13:56.900 --> 13:59.240
You know, did all this stuff in the bibliography.

13:59.980 --> 14:04.620
And it came out, I think it took about a week to write the story, but it was because

14:04.620 --> 14:10.500
we both of us knew certain parts, you know, already had done research in certain areas

14:11.000 --> 14:16.380
that we could write the story and use the other research we did as we wrote it to finish it.

14:16.780 --> 14:20.720
But we did research, but we already had a lot of research, too.

14:31.540 --> 14:34.460
All of Waldrop's stories are characterized by a lot of details.

14:35.000 --> 14:38.860
This prompted us to ask Waldrop how much research he does prior to his writing a story.

14:39.580 --> 14:43.260
It's like everybody says, and I know it's true, I researched too much.

14:43.540 --> 14:44.880
I researched everything too much.

14:44.900 --> 14:50.440
Every story I write, I research a whole bunch and then don't use half of it, you know?

14:50.580 --> 14:52.260
Don't use a third of it, usually something like that.

14:53.400 --> 14:56.880
I like certain research that I want to do, but I don't want to do it.

14:57.380 --> 15:00.560
On my own when I'm not sure what I'm doing.

15:00.960 --> 15:04.560
So I read a whole lot about the whole subject.

15:05.680 --> 15:08.080
And a lot of that works its way back into the story.

15:08.560 --> 15:14.760
When I know exactly what I want to do in a story, then I get real specific and that research is not as much fun.

15:14.940 --> 15:19.740
You know, because you're saying I need to know exactly when or exactly what or something like that.

15:19.900 --> 15:21.280
You know, and that's nice because then you got to look.

15:21.660 --> 15:26.360
Whereas if you don't know anything, not anything, but you don't know much about the field, you can just go

15:26.360 --> 15:31.120
and get everything on it and just start going through it and reading it and coming across fan, you know,

15:31.160 --> 15:33.880
fascinating little nuggets and stuff like that to use, you know?

15:34.700 --> 15:36.380
But I do too much research.

15:36.780 --> 15:38.840
I do way too much research for every story.

15:39.000 --> 15:44.380
And it's like sometimes the research will take a month and the story will take two days.

15:45.000 --> 15:45.820
You know, it's...

15:46.300 --> 15:49.540
We asked Walter if he considers this extra research to be wasted effort.

15:50.100 --> 15:51.320
Well, it's never wasted.

15:52.480 --> 15:59.580
It's only wasteful in the sense that I could possibly be doing the next thing down the line

15:59.580 --> 16:02.280
while I'm still doing the research on one thing.

16:02.580 --> 16:04.680
You know, I could already be through with the story and have it.

16:05.200 --> 16:11.560
But I do the research and it just shows up in the story, you know, in the story.

