Waldrop has had several works which made the final ballot in the Nebula voting,

17:57.400 --> 17:59.440
but The Ugly Chickens is his first winner.

18:05.460 --> 18:12.200
I have not mixed feelings, but I had no idea when I wrote Ugly Chickens how good it was or not.

18:12.200 --> 18:18.100
I hadn't written a story for about six months when I wrote that.

18:18.880 --> 18:22.120
I was doing other stuff and I was working on research on other things,

18:22.320 --> 18:24.580
and I hadn't written an actual story.

18:24.700 --> 18:29.320
So when I finally wrote Ugly Chickens, I didn't know if it was any good or not.

18:29.740 --> 18:32.700
I really didn't. I couldn't tell anymore. It worked on it so long, you know.

18:33.100 --> 18:36.600
I did all this research for the thing, like I did six months of research for it.

18:36.680 --> 18:38.060
It's way too long for a story.

18:38.580 --> 18:41.660
And then I wrote the story and I didn't know if the story was any good or not.

18:41.660 --> 18:47.780
And then I sent it off to Terry and like the thing was that Terry at the time was taking a lot of medicine.

18:47.780 --> 18:52.100
He had a really he'd wrenched his back and he was taking a lot of medicine and reading for

18:52.100 --> 18:57.060
universe at the same time. Universe filled up and he said I'd like to take it,

18:57.060 --> 18:58.960
but universe is filled up and all this stuff.

18:58.960 --> 19:02.240
And I said okay and about that time, Marta Randall called.

19:02.500 --> 19:06.360
You know, I just heard from Terry about the story and I want it real bad and

19:06.360 --> 19:08.420
will you take twice as much money for it?

19:08.420 --> 19:12.440
You know, and I said oh sure, right? You know, so she ran down the hill and got the story from

19:12.440 --> 19:18.480
Terry and brought, you know, and sent me a contract and like two nights later, I walk in the house

19:18.480 --> 19:23.080
and it's 12, 30 at night and the phone rings and says Howard, this is Terry.

19:23.620 --> 19:26.300
I could just see dollars flying out the window.

19:26.540 --> 19:33.060
I knew exactly what was going to happen, you know, and like he had gotten off his medicine

19:33.060 --> 19:39.420
and one of the stories he had been promised wasn't delivered and the person said I can't do it,

19:39.460 --> 19:44.520
you know, and he wanted the story back real bad and like he was trying, you know, he was trying

19:44.520 --> 19:49.820
politely to get the story back for less money than Marta was going to pay me and all this kind of.

19:50.140 --> 20:03.040
Anyway, I had no idea whether at the time, whether the story was any good or it was just Marta and

20:03.040 --> 20:08.240
I always try to hope that the next story, a writer one down the line is going to be,

20:08.360 --> 20:16.400
going to be my best, you know, and there's just no, you know, I like ugly chickens.

20:16.620 --> 20:21.380
It still holds up, I think, real well, if that's what you mean. I went back and re-read it about

20:22.040 --> 20:26.980
three months ago and it was still a good story, which is all you can hope for because some of

20:26.980 --> 20:31.880
them aren't, you know, or not, not they're not good, it's that they're not, not like you remember

20:31.880 --> 20:37.080
them or wanted them to be. The final 1983 Nebula Ballot featured a Waldrop story,

20:37.320 --> 20:42.380
God's Hooks. It's based on the meeting between two monumental literary figures, Isaac Walton and

20:42.380 --> 20:47.420
John Bunyan. And it's amazing that nobody had stuck those together and because they did,

20:48.020 --> 20:54.560
any, any time you look at a survey of English literature, the two books that are unclassifiable,

20:54.880 --> 20:58.360
the only two unclassifiable books in other words are like biographies and there were like

20:58.360 --> 21:03.360
histories and there were beginnings of novels and there were poetry and plays and all that,

21:03.520 --> 21:08.420
but the only two unclassifiable books they talk about are, are, is Pilgrim's Progress and The

21:08.420 --> 21:14.860
Complete Angler. You know, those are two totally, totally, you know, classical books and they're

21:14.860 --> 21:20.880
not like any other books written that century or before since, you know. It amazed me that nobody,

21:21.140 --> 21:26.200
nobody had put the two together and the obvious way to put the two together was, you know,

21:26.200 --> 21:30.360
